Palmer Penguins

In this homework we will use the penguins data set. This data set is part of the palmerpenguins package. You can load the data set by executing the command:

# install.packages('palmerpenguins')
data(penguins, package="palmerpenguins")

If the command above throws an error message about the package not found, make sure to install the palmerpenguins package on your machine.

The information in the penguins data is collected by several antarctic research teams, who took body measurements of different types of penguins in three different locations. See ?penguins for a description of all of the variables and a bit of the scientific background of this data.

  1. How does the length (bill_length_mm) of a penguins beak relate to its depth (bill_depth_mm)? Use the ggplot2 package to show a chart, describe the relationship in words. Describe the structure and propose a follow-up. (3 sentences: structure of the plot, what do you see, follow-up).
  • The charts below have plotted the bill length data on the x axis and the bill depth on the y axis. From the scatter plots it is not trivial to determine an exact correlation between the length and depth of the bills, however, within the scatterplot three discernible groups present themselves. For follow up to the scatter plots it would be interesting to see the correlation of the bill depth and length further divided by species, as the three groups likely correlate to the different species of penguins within the list.
ggplot(penguins, aes(x=bill_length_mm,y=bill_depth_mm))+geom_point()
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

  1. To investigate the group structure you see in the scatterplot above (this is a mega hint as to what you should be seeing :) ) you decide to add color to the above scatterplot. First, map island to color, then map species to color. Describe the relationship between length (bill_length_mm) of a penguins beak and its depth (bill_depth_mm) under these two color mappings. How do these color mappings inform the relationship between bill lengths and bill depths?

  • Scatter Plot 1 (island): The scatter plot using island as a color scheme doesnt offer very much more information. The correlation between length and depth does not become any more clear. Something that can be determined from this scatter plot is that all penguins from the Island of Torgersen appear to be grouped together. Within this group an ever so slight correlation between length and depth does appear. That is as the length gets longer the depth becomes deeper. The correlation is not strong however and a true linear correlation can not be stated with any reasonable probability.

  • Scatter Plot 2 (island): The scatter plot using the species as a third variable identifier offers more detail in the relationship of length and depth. An actual correlation between the length and depth can be seen when the species of the penguins are grouped. The correlation is positively linear and isnt very strong, but the correlation does in fact exist. The weakest of correlations comes from the Adelie species and the other two species have similar correlations.

ggplot(penguins, aes(x=bill_length_mm,y=bill_depth_mm,color=island))+geom_point()
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

ggplot(penguins, aes(x=bill_length_mm,y=bill_depth_mm,color=species))+geom_point()
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

  1. What is the exact relationship between species and islands? Draw a barchart and add some color. Make sure to describe the relationship in words.
  • The bar chart below is describing the penguin count on each island with a color identifier based on species. This means that we are able to visually see and gain a reasonable understanding of what type of species of penguin is located where. From the barchart we are able to draw the conclusion that just 1 species of penguin, the Adelle, lives on the island of Torgersen where as the other two islands contain two species of penguin. Another interesting fact gained from the barchart is that the Adelle species lives on all three islands, where as the Chinstrap only lives on Dream Island, and the Gentoo species only lives on Biscoe Island.
ggplot(penguins,aes(x=island,fill=species))+geom_bar()
